  'You are preparing an estate appraisal at 4417 Highway 29 North, Inman, SC 29349. The subject is 3BR/2BA · 1,520 SF · 1985-built SFR (updated 2008) · Rural Spartanburg County · 0.75 acres. Estate appraisal for estate tax filing. Date of death: 13 years ago. A major SCDOT interchange improvement project on I-26 at Highway 29 was completed approximately 8 years ago — approximately 5 years after the date of death. At the date of death, the interchange was a signalized at-grade crossing with no on/off ramp structure. The current full interchange did not exist at the effective date. Section 5 — Locational Influence — requires you to identify which locational factors were present at the subject as of the effective date, classify each as Positive, Negative, Neutral, or Market-Dependent based on the location profile evidence as it existed at that date, and write a brief market-supported rationale for each classification. The fundamental discipline of retrospective appraisal is that every factor identification must be grounded in evidence available at or before the effective date — current conditions are distractors. Factors that did not exist at the effective date must be left unchecked, and each rationale must cite specific period-appropriate evidence.'
