  'You are preparing an estate appraisal at 847 Poinsett Highway, Greenville, SC 29609. The subject is 3BR/2BA · 1,360 SF · 1955-built SFR (updated 2006) · Poinsett Highway Corridor. Estate appraisal for estate tax filing. Date of death: 15 years ago. The Poinsett Highway corridor has changed substantially in both directions over 15 years. At the date of death, the area was characterized by active industrial tenants, low residential reinvestment, and a corridor in measurable decline. Multiple conditions have changed since the effective date. Each factor must be established using period-specific documentation. Section 5 — Locational Influence — requires you to identify which locational factors were present at the subject as of the effective date, classify each as Positive, Negative, Neutral, or Market-Dependent based on the location profile evidence as it existed at that date, and write a brief market-supported rationale for each classification. The fundamental discipline of retrospective appraisal is that every factor identification must be grounded in evidence available at or before the effective date — current conditions are distractors. Factors that did not exist at the effective date must be left unchecked, and each rationale must cite specific period-appropriate evidence.'
