  '{"subject": {"address_summary": "1234 Cleveland Street, Greenville, SC 29601", "subject_summary": "3BR/1.5BA · 1,420 SF · 1952-built SFR (updated 2019) · Cleveland Park Fringe", "context_label": "Consulting Context", "context_text": "Private consulting assignment. Client is a value-add investor evaluating this property for long-term rental hold. The investor is specifically interested in neighborhood trajectory — whether observable market signals indicate an improving or declining trend — as a primary factor in the hold-value decision."}, "location_profile": ["The subject is located in the Cleveland Park fringe neighborhood of Greenville, approximately 1.8 miles from downtown and adjacent to Cleveland Park — a major Greenville County public park with athletic fields, a public pool, and walking trails. The immediate neighborhood has experienced documented reinvestment since 2016, reflected in active permit activity for renovations, increasing sale velocity, and rising median prices in MLS records over the past 4 years.", "1234 Cleveland Street is a through-street lot on a block with a mix of renovated and unrenovated single-family homes. Three adjacent properties on the block show recent renovation activity based on permit records and observation. A small neighborhood commercial strip approximately 0.25 miles north on Augusta Road includes a coffee shop, a yoga studio, and a sandwich restaurant opened within the past 3 years. The school zone is below-average for Greenville County. FEMA Zone X is confirmed. No HOA exists. Prisma Health''s downtown campus is approximately 2 miles east."], "factors": [{"id": "A", "label": "Improving neighborhood trajectory (documented reinvestment, rising prices, permit activity)"}, {"id": "B", "label": "Cleveland Park public amenity proximity (park, pool, trails)"}, {"id": "C", "label": "Emerging neighborhood retail (coffee shop, fitness, dining within 0.25 miles)"}, {"id": "D", "label": "Below-average school district"}, {"id": "E", "label": "Prisma Health downtown campus proximity (~2 miles)"}, {"id": "F", "label": "FEMA Zone X"}, {"id": "G", "label": "HOA restrictions limiting rental use"}, {"id": "H", "label": "Transmission line easement"}], "classification_options": ["Positive", "Negative", "Neutral", "Market-Dependent"], "min_rationale_chars": 20, "teaching_points": ["Teaching Point 1 — Trajectory is a locational factor, not a prediction. Factor A classifies the neighborhood trajectory as Positive based on documented, observable market signals — permit activity, MLS price trends, sale velocity. This is not a forecast; it is a classification of a measurable current condition. Students who resist classifying trajectory because the future is uncertain are confusing analysis with prediction. The appraiser analyzes what the market evidence currently shows.", "Teaching Point 2 — Emerging retail is a leading indicator, not a distractor. Factor C (new independent retail) is an analytically legitimate locational factor in investor analysis. New food, fitness, and lifestyle retail openings in a previously underserved area are documented early signals of investment momentum. Students who overlook this factor because it is not a traditional appraisal variable are applying a narrower analytical framework than investor-focused consulting requires.", "Teaching Point 3 — Trajectory improvement does not override structural negatives. Factor D (below-average school zone) remains a Negative despite the improving trajectory. An improving trajectory can narrow the impact of a structural negative over time, but it does not eliminate it — particularly for an investor whose exit strategy requires reaching an owner-occupant buyer. Students who reclassify D as Neutral because the neighborhood is improving are conflating current trajectory with resolved constraints."]}'::jsonb,
  '{"factors": {"A": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Documented reinvestment since 2016 with rising median prices, active permit activity, and increasing sale velocity are objective market signals supporting an improving trajectory classification. This is the most analytically prominent factor for a trajectory-focused investor."}, "B": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Adjacency to a major county park with recreational infrastructure is a documented positive for both owner-occupant buyers and rental tenants seeking active lifestyle amenities."}, "C": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "New independent retail openings are a leading indicator of neighborhood investment momentum — a positive locational signal that reinforces the trajectory classification."}, "D": {"present": true, "classification": "Negative", "rationale": "Below-average school zone is a Negative for the long-term investor exit strategy — it constrains the owner-occupant resale pool even if current rental demand is strong. Trajectory improvement does not eliminate this constraint."}, "E": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Medical employment proximity at 2 miles supports professional rental demand from healthcare workers — a stable tenant segment for a long-term hold strategy."}, "F": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Zone X confirmed."}, "G": {"present": false}, "H": {"present": false}}}'::jsonb
