  '',
  '{"subject": {"address_summary": "218 Kennedy Street, Spartanburg, SC 29303", "subject_summary": "3BR/2BA · 1,500 SF · 1958-built SFR (updated 2020) · Hub City District Fringe", "context_label": "Consulting Context", "context_text": "Private consulting assignment. Client is an investor evaluating this property for long-term rental hold in Spartanburg''s Hub City district fringe. The investor wants a full locational analysis identifying all rental demand drivers, trajectory signals, and factors affecting both current rental marketability and long-term hold value."}, "location_profile": ["The subject is located in the fringe of Spartanburg''s Hub City district, approximately 0.8 miles from Wofford College and 0.9 miles from Converse University. Combined enrollment at the two colleges is approximately 2,200 students, generating consistent rental demand for off-campus housing. USC Upstate''s downtown Spartanburg presence is approximately 0.5 miles away, adding a third educational demand source. Spartanburg Regional Medical Center is approximately 1.2 miles north.", "218 Kennedy Street is a through-street lot of 0.16 acres. The immediate block has a mix of owner-occupied renovated homes and investor-owned rental properties. Permit records document 6 renovation projects within 200 feet of the subject in the past 3 years. Spartanburg''s Morgan Square and the downtown amenity corridor are 0.9 miles east — a growing retail and dining district. The school zone is below-average for Spartanburg County. FEMA Zone X is confirmed. Kennedy Street carries light residential traffic. No HOA exists."], "factors": [{"id": "A", "label": "Wofford / Converse College proximity (~0.8–0.9 miles, ~2,200 students)"}, {"id": "B", "label": "USC Upstate downtown presence (~0.5 miles)"}, {"id": "C", "label": "Spartanburg Regional Medical Center proximity (~1.2 miles)"}, {"id": "D", "label": "Improving trajectory (documented permit activity, reinvestment within 200 ft)"}, {"id": "E", "label": "Downtown Spartanburg amenity corridor (~0.9 miles)"}, {"id": "F", "label": "Below-average school district"}, {"id": "G", "label": "FEMA Zone X"}, {"id": "H", "label": "HOA restrictions limiting rental use"}, {"id": "I", "label": "Industrial nuisance adjacency"}], "classification_options": ["Positive", "Negative", "Neutral", "Market-Dependent"], "min_rationale_chars": 20, "teaching_points": ["Teaching Point 1 — Demand source diversification is an investor-specific analytical framework. Owner-occupant analysis rarely distinguishes between one employer proximity and three. For an investor, having three independent demand sources (two colleges + medical center) creates demand resilience — if one source contracts, the others sustain occupancy. This is an investor-relevant consideration absent from owner-occupant analysis, and students working in a consulting context must build it into the locational framework.", "Teaching Point 2 — Trajectory and structural negatives coexist. Factor D (improving trajectory) and Factor F (below-average school zone) are both present simultaneously. The trajectory improvement may narrow the school zone constraint over time, but they are analytically independent in the current analysis. Students who cancel them against each other during the identification step are conflating identification with reconciliation.", "Teaching Point 3 — Multiple Positive factors require independent identification. This scenario has six present factors all classified Positive or better. Students who identify only the two or three most prominent ones are not performing a complete locational analysis. Completeness is especially important in consulting assignments where the investor is making a capital allocation decision based on the full locational picture, not a partial one."]}'::jsonb,
  '{"factors": {"A": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Dual-college proximity within one mile provides a stable off-campus rental demand base of approximately 2,200 students — a primary Positive rental demand driver for the investor tenant strategy."}, "B": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "A third educational demand source within 0.5 miles deepens the rental demand base beyond the two primary colleges, supporting demand diversification for a long-term hold strategy."}, "C": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Healthcare employment proximity at 1.2 miles adds a professional rental tenant segment independent of the student demand base — a diversification positive for investor demand analysis."}, "D": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Six renovation projects documented within 200 feet in 3 years is objective evidence of neighborhood reinvestment momentum — an improving trajectory classification supported by permit records."}, "E": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Growing retail and dining access within one mile supports lifestyle amenity demand from professional and student tenants alike — a positive that reinforces rental demand at this location."}, "F": {"present": true, "classification": "Negative", "rationale": "Below-average school zone constrains the owner-occupant resale pool and is a Negative for investor exit strategy, even where current rental demand is strong."}, "G": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Zone X confirmed."}, "H": {"present": false}, "I": {"present": false}}}'::jsonb
