ict"}, {"id": "D", "label": "Commercial strip / convenience store (~0.3 miles, pedestrian amenity for students)"}, {"id": "E", "label": "Periodic weekend noise from college events"}, {"id": "F", "label": "FEMA Zone X"}, {"id": "G", "label": "HOA restrictions limiting rental use"}, {"id": "H", "label": "Transmission line or industrial easement"}], "classification_options": ["Positive", "Negative", "Neutral", "Market-Dependent"], "min_rationale_chars": 20, "teaching_points": ["Teaching Point 1 — The same factor can have different analytical implications by client type. Factor C (below-average school zone) is Negative in both owner-occupant and investor analyses, but for different reasons. For an owner-occupant, it constrains buyer demand directly. For an investor targeting students, it does not constrain tenant demand — but it does constrain the resale exit pool. Students must not only classify correctly but explain the investor-specific reason for the classification. The consulting report must address both.", "Teaching Point 2 — Commercial proximity near a college is not automatically negative. Factor D (convenience store, 0.3 miles) is a pedestrian amenity for students — a Positive in this investor context. The same commercial use might be Neutral or Negative for a family residential assignment. Classification depends on what the market evidence shows for the specific tenant segment at this specific location. Context governs.", "Teaching Point 3 — Noise as Market-Dependent in a segmented rental market. Weekend event noise (Factor E) is accepted or expected by the student tenant segment but would deter professional or family renters. This is a genuine Market-Dependent factor where tenant segment determines direction — and where the investor''s chosen strategy determines how the appraiser should weigh it in the consulting narrative. The analytical obligation is to identify and classify it accurately; the strategic weighting is the investor''s decision."]}'::jsonb,
  '{"factors": {"A": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Half-mile proximity to Wofford College is a primary rental demand driver for the off-campus student and junior faculty segment — a strong Positive for an investor targeting this tenant base."}, "B": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Secondary demand source 1.5 miles away adds demand depth and diversification — a Positive for investor analysis, though less proximate than Wofford."}, "C": {"present": true, "classification": "Negative", "rationale": "Below-average school zone is a Negative for the long-term investor exit strategy — it limits the owner-occupant resale pool regardless of tenant demand strength. The investor classification is Negative, though the analytical reason differs from the owner-occupant analysis."}, "D": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "A pedestrian-accessible convenience retail option 0.3 miles away is a Positive pedestrian amenity for the student tenant segment — analytically distinct from an auto-oriented commercial nuisance at close proximity."}, "E": {"present": true, "classification": "Market-Dependent", "rationale": "Weekend event noise is accepted — or expected — by student tenants but may deter professional or family renters. Market-Dependent reflects the genuine split in tenant response based on segment, which the investor must evaluate against the intended tenant strategy."}, "F": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Zone X confirmed."}, "G": {"present": false}, "H": {"present": false}}}'::jsonb
