traffic, commercial trucks)"}, {"id": "C", "label": "Light industrial parts supplier (~0.35 miles, audible daytime operations)"}, {"id": "D", "label": "Stable trajectory (no significant reinvestment or decline signals)"}, {"id": "E", "label": "I-26 regional connectivity (~3 miles)"}, {"id": "F", "label": "Average school district"}, {"id": "G", "label": "FEMA Zone X"}, {"id": "H", "label": "Improving residential trajectory (not supported by evidence in this scenario)"}, {"id": "I", "label": "University or college rental demand driver"}], "classification_options": ["Positive", "Negative", "Neutral", "Market-Dependent"], "min_rationale_chars": 20, "teaching_points": ["Teaching Point 1 — Stable trajectory is Neutral, not Positive. Factor D requires precise classification. A stable corridor with no documented reinvestment signals is Neutral — not an improving opportunity and not a declining risk. Students who default to Positive because stability implies reliability are overstating the investment thesis. For a value-add or appreciation-oriented investor, Neutral trajectory may be a disqualifying condition. The analyst''s job is to classify accurately, not to optimize.", "Teaching Point 2 — The employer proximity positive and the corridor negative coexist. Factor A (Michelin proximity) and Factors B and C (corridor negatives) all relate to the same industrial corridor — but they are analytically independent. The employer creates the demand; the corridor character constrains the residential amenity. Both are present, both must be identified, and both affect investor returns from different directions.", "Teaching Point 3 — Industrial corridor analysis is distinct from suburban residential. Students who apply suburban residential locational frameworks to an industrial corridor assignment are using the wrong analytical lens. In an industrial corridor, employment proximity is a primary driver; residential character standards are secondary; and trajectory analysis focuses on industrial sector health rather than retail amenity development. The investor consulting context requires an analytically appropriate framework for the specific market type."]}'::jsonb,
  '{"factors": {"A": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Michelin''s multi-plant presence within 2.5 miles is a primary rental demand driver for the manufacturing worker tenant segment — a stable, documented Positive for a long-term hold strategy in this corridor."}, "B": {"present": true, "classification": "Negative", "rationale": "Reidville Road through-traffic including commercial trucks at a 28-foot setback is a Negative residential amenity condition that constrains the residential buyer and tenant pool — particularly relevant for investor exit analysis."}, "C": {"present": true, "classification": "Negative", "rationale": "Audible industrial operations within 0.35 miles are a documented Negative proximity externality — daytime noise constrains the residential character and limits tenant options to those who accept the industrial corridor environment."}, "D": {"present": true, "classification": "Neutral", "rationale": "Stable trajectory with no documented positive or negative momentum is Neutral — not an improving investment thesis, but not a deteriorating one. For a hold-strategy investor, stability without growth limits appreciation upside."}, "E": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "I-26 access within 3 miles provides regional employment connectivity beyond Michelin — supportive of a diversified tenant base across the broader Spartanburg County manufacturing and logistics corridor."}, "F": {"present": true, "classification": "Neutral", "rationale": "Average school zone with no documented premium — Neutral in an investor-rental context targeting manufacturing workers."}, "G": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Zone X confirmed."}, "H": {"present": false}, "I": {"present": false}}}'::jsonb
FROM scenarios s
JOIN scenario_categories sc ON sc.id = s.category_id
JOIN module_sections ms ON ms.id = sc.section_id
