  '{"subject": {"address_summary": "2847 Augusta Road, Greenville, SC 29605", "subject_summary": "4BR/2.5BA · 2,060 SF · 1978-built SFR (renovated 2021) · Augusta Road / Overbrook", "context_label": "Consulting Context", "context_text": "Private consulting assignment. Client is an institutional investor evaluating this property as part of a portfolio acquisition. The investor requires a comprehensive locational analysis that explicitly distinguishes factors affecting immediate rental marketability from factors affecting long-term hold value and exit strategy — and that identifies any factors whose analytical classification would differ between an owner-occupant appraisal and this investor consulting assignment."}, "location_profile": ["The subject is located on Augusta Road in Greenville''s Overbrook corridor, approximately 1.4 miles from downtown and within the Augusta Road retail and dining district — one of Greenville''s established lifestyle commercial corridors. The corridor has experienced reinvestment since 2012 with documented rising prices and active permit activity. GHS Patewood Medical Campus is approximately 3 miles east; Prisma Health downtown is approximately 1.8 miles northeast. The subject is in a below-average Greenville County school zone.", "2847 Augusta Road is a through-street lot with a 24-foot setback from Augusta Road, a four-lane urban arterial carrying approximately 14,000 vehicles per day. A neighborhood-scale coffee shop and wine bar occupy the commercial building immediately adjacent to the north — active daytime and evening operations with parking activity on the shared street. The Swamp Rabbit Trail runs approximately 0.6 miles east. FEMA Zone X is confirmed. The City of Greenville''s STR overlay zone covers the subject address. No HOA exists. The Augusta Road corridor is subject to a City-adopted streetscape improvement plan with funded infrastructure work scheduled within 18 months."], "factors": [{"id": "A", "label": "Augusta Road arterial frontage (~14,000 vehicles/day, 24-ft setback)"}, {"id": "B", "label": "Adjacent coffee shop and wine bar (immediate north, active evening operations)"}, {"id": "C", "label": "Augusta Road retail/dining district (walkable, 0.3-mile radius)"}, {"id": "D", "label": "Improving trajectory (documented reinvestment since 2012)"}, {"id": "E", "label": "Funded streetscape improvement plan (18-month timeline)"}, {"id": "F", "label": "Prisma Health / GHS Patewood employment proximity (1.8–3 miles)"}, {"id": "G", "label": "Below-average school district"}, {"id": "H", "label": "FEMA Zone X"}, {"id": "I", "label": "STR overlay zone (licensing currently available)"}, {"id": "J", "label": "Swamp Rabbit Trail (~0.6 miles)"}, {"id": "K", "label": "HOA restrictions limiting rental use"}, {"id": "L", "label": "FEMA Zone AE flood hazard"}], "classification_options": ["Positive", "Negative", "Neutral", "Market-Dependent"], "min_rationale_chars": 20, "teaching_points": ["Teaching Point 1 — The investor consulting analysis has more present factors than owner-occupant analysis would. This scenario has 10 present factors — more than most owner-occupant appraisal assignments would identify. The additional factors include trajectory, STR use rights, funded infrastructure, and demand diversification considerations that are not typically foregrounded in a standard residential appraisal. This does not mean the owner-occupant appraiser is wrong — it means the investor consulting framework asks different analytical questions that surface additional locational dimensions.", "Teaching Point 2 — Adjacent active commercial use is Market-Dependent, not uniformly Negative or Positive. Factor B (adjacent coffee shop and wine bar) illustrates a classic investor analytical challenge: the same use that creates lifestyle proximity value for one tenant segment creates noise and parking concerns for another. The analytical obligation is Market-Dependent — the investor must determine which tenant segment dominates demand at this specific location before assigning direction.", "Teaching Point 3 — Funded infrastructure is analytically distinct from general trajectory. Factor E (streetscape plan) and Factor D (improving trajectory) are both Positive but for different reasons — D reflects documented historical momentum; E reflects a specific, funded, time-bounded future improvement. Students who collapse them into a single trajectory factor are losing a distinction that matters for investor hold-period analysis. A funded infrastructure catalyst may accelerate value improvement in a way that general trajectory momentum alone would not predict."]}'::jsonb,
  '{"factors": {"A": {"present": true, "classification": "Negative", "rationale": "Direct frontage on a 4-lane arterial at 24 feet is a Negative for residential amenity — noise and commercial character concerns constrain both the tenant pool and the eventual owner-occupant resale market."}, "B": {"present": true, "classification": "Market-Dependent", "rationale": "Adjacent active food and beverage use generates foot traffic and noise that some tenants and buyers value as lifestyle proximity; others discount for parking activity and evening noise. Market-Dependent reflects this genuine split — direction differs by tenant segment."}, "C": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Walkable access to an established lifestyle retail and dining corridor is a documented Positive for both long-term professional renters and STR guests — supporting both rental strategies."}, "D": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Over a decade of documented reinvestment with rising prices is a strong improving trajectory signal — a primary Positive for long-term hold value and investor exit strategy."}, "E": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "City-funded infrastructure improvements with a defined 18-month timeline are a near-term catalyst for corridor value improvement — a Positive distinct from the general trajectory because it is funded, scheduled, and specific."}, "F": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Dual medical employment campuses within 3 miles support the professional long-term rental tenant base with documented healthcare worker demand in the Augusta Road submarket."}, "G": {"present": true, "classification": "Negative", "rationale": "Below-average school zone constrains owner-occupant exit market — a Negative for long-term hold value analysis regardless of strong current rental demand and improving trajectory."}, "H": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Zone X confirmed."}, "I": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "STR overlay zone coverage with current licensing availability represents an existing use right that adds hold-value flexibility for the dual-strategy investor."}, "J": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Trail access within 0.6 miles is a documented Positive for both professional tenants and STR guests in Greenville''s established urban residential market."}, "K": {"present": false}, "L": {"present": false}}}'::jsonb
